# README-First Session Rule

For every new session, review project reference documentation before proposing code changes, plans, or architecture decisions.

## Required startup reads

1. `README.md` (root project end-to-end reference)
2. `pirx-backend/migrations/README.md` (schema and migration order)
3. `pirx-frontend/README.md` (frontend baseline notes)

## Behavior requirements

- Treat the root `README.md` as the primary source of current architecture, data flow, and ML calculation definitions.
- If code and README appear inconsistent, verify code, then update docs as part of the same workstream.
- Before major changes, confirm impacted path across ingest, features, projection, API, frontend, and chat.
- Keep terminology aligned with project standards documented in the README and skills.
- Automatically update README docs in the same session when changes affect behavior, formulas, data flow, routes, schema, tasks, integrations, or architecture.
- Do not mark work complete until README updates are finished and reflect the implemented code.

## Auto-update triggers (must update docs)

Update one or more README files whenever changes touch:

- ML calculations, constants, thresholds, scoring labels, or projection/readiness formulas
- Data flow or orchestration across sync, cleaning, feature, projection, chat, or realtime stages
- API endpoints, request/response shapes, auth/dependency flow, or route behavior
- Database migrations, schema/table/index changes, or task scheduling behavior
- Frontend rendering logic that changes how projection/driver/readiness outputs are presented

## README update targets

- Root system reference: `README.md`
- Schema and migration reference: `pirx-backend/migrations/README.md`
- Frontend reference notes: `pirx-frontend/README.md`

Update only the files impacted by the change, but always check all three for consistency.

## Quick preflight checklist

- Read the three README files above
- Confirm affected modules and data flow touchpoints
- Validate migration assumptions before DB/schema changes
- Proceed with TDD and update docs when behavior changes
- Before finalizing, verify README content matches the implemented code paths and formulas

## README delta template (use on every relevant change)

When updating docs, add/refresh content using this structure:

- **What changed**: One-line description of implemented behavior/code change.
- **Why it changed**: One-line rationale (bug fix, feature, refactor, alignment).
- **Code touchpoints**: Paths of changed modules/routes/tasks/components.
- **Data-flow impact**: Which stage(s) changed (ingest, clean, features, projection, API, frontend, chat, realtime).
- **Formula/constant changes**: Old -> new values/equations/thresholds (or "none").
- **API/schema impact**: Endpoint contract or migration/table/index changes (or "none").
- **Verification**: Tests/commands/checks performed and result.

Use this template in:

- `README.md` for architecture/data-flow/ML behavior changes
- `pirx-backend/migrations/README.md` for DB/migration changes
- `pirx-frontend/README.md` for frontend behavior/integration changes
